  "prompt": "What oozes out of a bug bite?",
  "response": "When a bug bites, it often injects saliva into the skin to prevent blood clotting and facilitate feeding. The body's immune response to this foreign substance can cause various reactions. Here\u2019s what might ooze out of a bug bite:\n\n1. **Clear Fluid** (Serum): The most common ooze from a bug bite is clear fluid, which is part of the inflammatory response. This fluid helps to flush out irritants and heal the area.\n\n2. **Pus**: If the bite becomes infected (often due to scratching or bacteria entering the wound), it may ooze pus, a thick, yellowish or white fluid composed of dead white blood cells, bacteria, and tissue debris.\n\n3. **Blood**: Sometimes, a bug bite may bleed, especially if it\u2019s scratched or irritated.\n\n4. **Lymph Fluid**: This is a clear to slightly yellowish fluid that is part of the body\u2019s immune system. It may leak out if the bite is particularly inflamed.\n\nIf the bite is oozing excessively, swollen, red, warm, or accompanied by fever or other systemic symptoms, it could indicate an infection or allergic reaction, and medical attention may be necessary.",
